---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { withBase } from '../../lib/site';
---

<Base title="Docs" description="Getting started with Cardo: install, build your first dashboard, keyboard shortcuts, self-test – plus honest answers to common questions.">
  <h1>Docs</h1>
  <p class="muted">
    Everything you need to get from “installed” to “this is my place now”. Short on purpose –
    Cardo is meant to explain itself.
  </p>

  <section class="card" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
    <h2>Getting started</h2>
    <ol class="steps">
      <li>
        <strong>Install Cardo.</strong> Grab it from the <a href={withBase('/download')}>download page</a> –
        one command or one installer, no setup, no account.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Build your first dashboard.</strong> Cardo opens on a blank canvas. Press
        <kbd>Cmd/Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>E</kbd> to enter <em>edit mode</em>, then add widgets and
        place, move and resize them until it feels right. Multiple pages (work, home, focus)
        are yours to create.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Learn the palette.</strong> <kbd>Cmd/Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>K</kbd> opens the command
        palette – the fastest way to add widgets, switch pages or change the theme without
        hunting through menus.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Let Cardo check itself.</strong> In the settings you'll find a
        <em>self-test</em> button. One click, and Cardo tests itself end to end and shows you a
        readable report. Run it whenever something feels off.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section class="card" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
    <h2>FAQ</h2>

    <details>
      <summary>Where is my data?</summary>
      <p>
        On your device, and nowhere else. Cardo stores everything in a local SQLite database,
        and your notes live as plain files in your notes folder – readable without Cardo, and
        yours to back up however you like. Nothing is uploaded, ever, unless a tool's
        transparency light is yellow and tells you exactly what it sends and where.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Is it really free?</summary>
      <p>
        Yes. Free download, all features included, no trial, no ads. Cardo is funded by
        voluntary <a href={withBase('/donate')}>donations</a> that cover the year's running costs – shown
        transparently as a percentage. Donating changes nothing about what the app can do.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>When does sync come?</summary>
      <p>
        Sync between your devices is planned as an optional later feature. It will be key-based:
        you generate a key, your data is end-to-end encrypted with it, and the server can never
        read anything. It's off by default – if you never turn it on, Cardo stays 100 % offline,
        exactly as it is today.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>What does the traffic light on a tool mean?</summary>
      <p>
        Green: the tool works fully local, nothing leaves your device. Yellow: the tool contacts
        the internet – and it tells you in plain language what it sends, where it goes, and why,
        before anything happens. There is no hidden third state.
      </p>
    </details>
  </section>

  <style>
    .steps li { margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
    details { margin-top: 0.75rem; }
    summary { cursor: pointer; font-weight: 600; }
    details p { margin: 0.5rem 0 0.75rem; }
  </style>
</Base>
